om/sonatype/sonatype-guide-cursor-plugin/blob/main/INSTALL_TEST.md\"},{\"title\":\"Cursor 2.5: Plugins - Release Discussions - Cursor - Community Forum\",\"url\":\"https://forum.cursor.com/t/cursor-2-5-plugins/152124\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's information about Cursor IDE plugin manifests, plugin.json, skills, and local installation paths:\n\n## Plugin Manifest Structure\n\nThe only required file for a Cursor plugin is .cursor-plugin/plugin.json, which includes fields like name, version, description, author, and paths to commands, skills, and rules directories.\n\n## Skills in Plugins\n\nSkills are SKILL.md files in named subdirectories — the agent invokes them based on task context. If you don't specify paths in plugin.json, Cursor auto-discovers components from the default directory names, and explicit paths override auto-discovery.\n\n## Local Installation Path\n\nFor local installation, you need the full ~/.cursor/plugins/<n>/ path. More specifically, don't install under ~/.cursor/skills/ only, as skills get loaded but commands don't register; you need the full ~/.cursor/plugins/<n>/ path plus the .claude/ registration.\n\n## Development Approach\n\nClaude Code CLI has --plugin-dir ./my-plugin for local testing, where you point it at your plugin directory and it loads everything. However, Cursor IDE doesn't have that flag, and the Marketplace is the intended distribution channel with no built-in \"load from local directory\" option in the IDE.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"d282aa1a-40a2-4796-9fd6-295f1004cbf9","timestamp":"2026-04-23T23:58:02.597Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Cursor IDE plugin manifest plugin.json skills local install path 2026","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_012TntBocL17jzhsm5xB4RXQ","content":[{"title":"How to Write and Test Cursor Plugins Locally (The Part the Docs Don’t Tell You) | by Vitek Tajzich | Mar, 2026 | Medium","url":"https://m